      <hedline>
        <hl1>Share a Missile Defense</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sherman K Poultney letter suggests allowing Russia to buy national missile defense system if it is built, to maintain balance of power (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One of the most frequent (and rational) criticisms of a proposed national missile defense system (front page, April 26) is that it would disrupt the current balance of power. One way to alleviate this concern both with Russia and with the opposition in the United States is to offer to let Russia buy such a system from us and install it in Russia.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One of the most frequent (and rational) criticisms of a proposed national missile defense system (front page, April 26) is that it would disrupt the current balance of power. One way to alleviate this concern both with Russia and with the opposition in the United States is to offer to let Russia buy such a system from us and install it in Russia.</p>
        <p>In that way, the balance of power would remain intact; both the United States and Russia could protect against an attack from a rogue nation; and American businesses would doubly profit.</p>
        <p>SHERMAN K. POULTNEY  Wilton, Conn., April 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
